Installation
lazy.nvim:
{
  "riccardo-enr/devcontainer.nvim",
  cmd = {
    "DevcontainerUp", "DevcontainerDown", "DevcontainerRebuild",
    "DevcontainerExec", "DevcontainerShell", "DevcontainerStatus",
    "DevcontainerLog", "DevcontainerTemplate", "DevcontainerVariant",
  },
  opts = {},
}

The RPC proxy
lsp_cmd plugs a small proxy between the LSP client on the host and the LSP server inside the container. The proxy reads JSON-RPC frames from stdio and rewrites URI-typed fields in both directions, driven by a lookup table built from the vendored LSP metaModel.json.





sequenceDiagram
    participant Client as nvim LSP client (host)
    participant Proxy as RPC proxy
    participant Server as LSP server (container)
    Client-&gt;&gt;Proxy: textDocument/definition { uri: file:///host/... }
    Proxy-&gt;&gt;Server: { uri: file:///workspaces/repo/... }
    Server--&gt;&gt;Proxy: location { uri: file:///workspaces/repo/... }
    Proxy--&gt;&gt;Client: location { uri: file:///host/... }






Container-side paths that live outside the workspaceFolder (system headers, language runtimes) are exposed under a read-only docker://&lt;container_id&gt;/&lt;abs-container-path&gt; URI scheme. A BufReadCmd autocmd fetches them on demand via devcontainer exec cat, so go-to-definition works without bind-mounting /usr/include.

auto_up and lazy container startup
By default the user runs :DevcontainerUp manually. With auto_up = true, the first LSP attach triggers devcontainer up in the background and queues outbound JSON-RPC frames until the container is ready, then drains them into the live proxy. See ADR-0007 for the design trade-off (in particular the unbounded queue during up).
require("devcontainer").setup({
  auto_up = true,  -- default: false
})
